{
  "card_id": "reversal_vs_continuation",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Reversal vs Continuation",
  "aliases": [
    "Next Candle Model",
    "Next Day Model",
    "previous candle model",
    "Previous Candle Model"
  ],
  "school": "Price Action",
  "definition": "A reversal occurs when price takes out the previous candle's high or low but closes back inside its range, signaling a potential opposite move next. A continuation occurs when price closes outside the range, signaling the trend will persist. The model uses the previous candle's close relative to its range to predict the next candle's direction, with reliability enhanced by PD arrays, swing points, and price delivery phases.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Price must first take out the previous candle's high or low.",
    "For a reversal, the candle must close back inside the prior range.",
    "For a continuation, the candle must close outside the prior range.",
    "If a swing point is taken but the close is inside, treat as a conflict and wait for another candle.",
    "Align with phases of price delivery (expansion, retracement, etc.) to filter signals.",
    "Identify whether the previous candle respects PD arrays (FVG, OB, etc.) or swing highs/lows; failure to close beyond that structure triggers reversal expectation.",
    "Must wait for the previous candle to fully close before judging direction."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Provides a bias framework for the next candle: a reversal close anticipates a move opposite the break; a continuation close anticipates a move in the same direction. Use with points of interest (order blocks, fair value gaps) and confirmation of change in state of delivery on lower time frames to enter with defined risk and targets. Can drill down to hourly or 15-minute charts for specific entries, using prior day high/low or swing points as stops and targets.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Mechanically applying the model without considering price delivery phase, leading to counter-trend trades in expansions.",
    "Not waiting for the previous candle to fully close before predicting the next.",
    "Ignoring the close position and only looking at whether high/low was taken (must close inside for reversal).",
    "Not confirming that price truly respected PD arrays or swing points, relying on visual judgment.",
    "Trading when multiple signals conflict (e.g., swing high sweep vs. inside close) without waiting for more candles.",
    "Ignoring higher-order structures like MSS, causing predictions to fail.",
    "Expecting the pattern to work 100% without additional confluences.",
    "Applying the model in unstable market structures."
  ],
